{{For|other uses of the phrase|Cheating Death (disambiguation)}}
{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}
[[Image:Taby kyrka Death playing chess.jpg|thumb|The medieval painting of Death playing chess from [[Täby|Täby Church]] in [[Sweden]].]]
The phrase '''cheating death''' is commonly used to describe the manner in which a person avoids a possibly fatal event or who prolongs their life in spite of considerable odds. A person who cures themselves of [[cancer]] without [[chemotherapy]], a person who avoids by a narrow margin falling off a cliff or building or being shot or stabbed, or a person who survives hospitalization in [[critical condition]] in spite of a poor [[prognosis]] from doctors all might be described as having "cheated death". In [[Greek mythology]], [[Sisyphus]] cheated death twice: by trapping [[Thanatos]] in his own chains and then by tricking [[Persephone]] into letting him return. He was finally sentenced to eternal fruitless labor in [[Tartarus]] for his presumption.

Although it is difficult to find information about the origin of the phrase, it may be related to [[anthropomorphism]] of [[death]], more commonly known in the [[English-speaking world]] as [[the Grim Reaper]]. Such personification has also led to a wide variety of [[popular culture|pop-culture]] references, such as in [[Ingmar Bergman|Ingmar Bergman's]] film ''[[The Seventh Seal]]'', in which a knight proposes a wager with death over a game of [[chess]]. In the film the knight comments that he knows death plays chess because he's seen it in paintings, possibly in reference to a medieval painting of death playing chess which hangs in [[Täby church|Täby Church]] in [[Sweden]]. Playing chess offers the knight an opportunity to [[cheating in chess|cheat]].

Cheating death is also a recurring theme in the [[Final Destination (film series)|''Final Destination'' film series]].

