{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2011}} '''Germaine Monteil''' was a New York-based French fashion designer and [[cosmetician]] who founded the cosmetics and [[perfume]] company sharing her name.
==Fashion== Born in France in 1898, Monteil moved to the United States in the early 1930s. A high-end dressmaker as well as a [[cosmetician]], she first established herself as a fashion designer.<ref name=asiv>{{cite book| last = Hall| first = Daniel Delis| title = As Seen In Vogue: A Century of American Fashion in Advertising| publisher=Texas Tech University Press| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MvilOZhaRkAC&pg=PA67&dq#v=onepage&q&f=false| year = 2007| pages =67| ISBN = 0-89672-616-9}}</ref> She made classic dresses with flaring circular or pleated skirts and slim silhouettes, and was renowned for her use of prints which appealed to the American market.<ref name=asiv/> In 1938, Monteil won a [[Neiman Marcus Fashion Award]] in recognition of her influence upon the fashion industry. This was the first year in which the awards were presented. She died in 1987.
==Cosmetics & perfumes== In 1936, Monteil founded with her husband, Guy Bjorkman, ''Germaine Monteil Cosmetiques Corp.'' as a sideline to her fashion business, offering skin treatments and creams.<ref name=asiv/><ref>Sagarin, Edward; {{cite book| last = Balsam| first = M.S| title = Cosmetics, science and technology (2nd edition)| publisher=Wiley-Interscience| year = 1972| pages =217| ISBN = 0-471-04649-3}}</ref> Her first perfume, ''Laughter'' (later renamed ''Rigolade''), came out in 1941.<ref name=nph>Young, Duane A. & {{cite book| last = Jones-North| first = Jacqueline Y.| title = Commercial Perfume Bottles (2nd edition)| publisher=Schiffer Pub.| year = 1987| pages =| ISBN = 0-88740-108-2}}</ref> The increasing success of this sideline led to Monteil abandoning fashion design in the late 1940s to focus on perfume and cosmetics.<ref name=asiv/> The company was acquired by cosmetics giant Revlon in 1987 from fashion house Yves Saint Laurent. Revlon then sold the brand on to the German company Wilde Cosmetics GmbH in 2006.
Monteil fragrances include:
{{col-begin}}{{col-3}} * '''1940s:''' * ''Laughter'' * ''New Love'' * ''Nostalgia'' * ''Frou Frou'' {{col-3}} * '''1950s:''' * ''Fleur Savage'' * ''Gigolo'' * ''Nouvel Amour'' * ''Rigolade'' {{col-3}} * '''1990s:''' * ''L'Eau de Monteil'' (1996) {{col-end}}
